---
/**
 * The three capabilities the crate README states first: counterfactual
 * dynamics, native regime change, native multiphysics.
 *
 * Each panel states what the crate does, shows the code or run output that
 * does it, and gives the measured figure. Every figure is quoted from a
 * committed run.
 */

const config = `// The configuration layer: an owned description of the problem.
let solver = CfdConfigBuilder::dec_ns()
    .viscosity(nu)
    .time_step(dt)
    .warm_start()
    .build()?;

let config = CfdConfigBuilder::march::<2, FloatType>("viv-wake")
    .mesh(Mesh::box_domain([nx, ny])
        .spacing(ft(h_spec))
        .immersed(Body::disk(center, ft(0.5))))
    .solver(solver)
    .zones(zones)                                  // inflow, outflow, slip walls
    .seed(Seed::UniformX { speed: 1.0 })
    .march_for(STEPS)
    .observe(Observe::default().probe([center[0] + ft(1.5), center[1]]))
    .build()?;`;

const flow = `// The flow layer: materialize a run from that description.
let report = CfdFlow::march(&config).run_owned()?;

// Or march a coupled run until a predicate fires, then fork the pause.
let onset = CfdFlow::march(&nominal)
    .couple(world::corridor_coupling(1.0, 0))
    .from_field(world::initial_field())
    .until(|field, _| field.regime().map(|r| r.gnss_denied).unwrap_or(false))?;

let corridor = CfdFlow::study("bank-angle corridor")
    .cases(model::coarse_commands())
    .fork(&onset)                            // the shared flow-resolved fork point
    .branch(model::bank_world)               // one description per candidate
    .continue_for(constants::BRANCH_STEPS)   // concurrent, copy-on-write
    .reduce_all(model::score_branches)
    .gates(model::corridor_gates())
    .verdict()?;`;

const regimeLog = `regime -> slip (GNSS-available), Kn=0.07829109848665225
regime -> slip (GNSS-denied),    Kn=0.01705925949914955
regime -> continuum (GNSS-denied), Kn=0.009938308574526865
regime -> continuum (GNSS-available), Kn=0.00025839060489290773`;

const coupling = `Coupling::between_steps()
    .then(VibrationalLagStage::new(/* Millikan-White bath */))
    .then(FiniteRateIonizationStage::new(n_tot).with_density_field("n_tot"))
    .then(RegimeClassify::new(l_char, trigger))
    .then(BankSteeredLift::new(rho_ref, cda_over_m, l_over_d))
    .then(TrajectoryNav::new(q_diag, gnss_var, optical_var).with_imu(imu))
    .then(CyberneticCorrect::new(SafetyEnvelope::new(q_max, g_max, bank_max)))
    .build()`;

const axes = [
  {
    name: 'Flow regime',
    on: 'freestream Knudsen number',
    body: 'Selects the governing model: continuum Navier–Stokes, slip-corrected continuum, transitional, or free-molecular.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Dynamics regime',
    on: 'force ratio ε = a_aero/a_grav',
    body: 'While gravity dominates, the trajectory advances on the exact KS-conformal core with aero as a between-step kick. Once aero dominates, it switches to direct Cowell integration.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Link regime',
    on: 'evolved electron density',
    body: 'The electron density sets the plasma frequency, and the plasma frequency decides whether the GNSS link exists. The Kalman filter’s measurement gating follows it.',
  },
];
---
<section class="caps page" data-rise>
  <header class="sec-head">
    <p class="eyebrow eyebrow-coord">
      <span class="ix">01 / 04</span><span class="lb">Capabilities</span>
    </p>
    <h2>How a run is structured</h2>
    <p class="lede">
      Counterfactual dynamics, regime change, and multiphysics coupling are
      reached through one <code>CfdFlow</code> language and one scalar type.
      A runnable example with a committed output file demonstrates each.
    </p>
  </header>

  <!-- 1 -->
  <article class="cap panel corner-brackets rise" style="--i:0">
    <div class="cap-head">
      <p class="cap-ix num">01</p>
      <div>
        <h3>Counterfactual dynamics</h3>
        <p class="cap-claim">A paused run forks into candidate worlds.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="cap-body">
      A program is written in two layers. The configuration layer holds owned
      descriptions: mesh, solver, boundary zones, seed, stop condition, and
      observables. Building one is separate from running it.
    </p>

    <pre><code>{config}</code></pre>

    <p class="cap-body">
      The flow layer materializes runs from those descriptions.
      <code>march</code> advances a run until a predicate fires and yields a
      resumable pause; <code>study</code> forks that pause once per candidate
      and continues each branch in its own alternated world.
    </p>

    <pre><code>{flow}</code></pre>

    <p class="cap-body">
      Because a description is a value, a counterfactual is the same flow handed
      a different description. A fork shares the paused state in O(1) through
      copy-on-write, covering tensor fields, navigation engine, and provenance
      log. Every branch stamps a <code>!!ContextAlternation!!</code> marker
      naming its baseline, and fan-outs run on scoped threads that produce bits
      identical to the sequential run.
    </p>

    <ul class="cap-nums">
      <li>Fork setup measured at 42 ns; continuation costs 0.67–1.04× the trunk.</li>
      <li>The corridor commits the best of seventeen worlds mid-descent.</li>
      <li>A mid-burn fork of a marched plume-coupled state departs a frozen-drag prediction by 139.4 m/s.</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="cap-more">
      <a href="/tutorial/stage-1-corridor/">Walk 1: how the fork is built</a>
      <a href="/blueprints/fork-a-running-simulation/">Blueprint: fork a running simulation</a>
    </p>
  </article>

  <!-- 2 -->
  <article class="cap panel corner-brackets rise" style="--i:1">
    <div class="cap-head">
      <p class="cap-ix num">02</p>
      <div>
        <h3>Native regime change</h3>
        <p class="cap-claim">The governing model follows a measured quantity, step by step.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="cap-body">
      The regime is a classified property of the evolved state rather than a
      configured stage. A vehicle entering or leaving orbit crosses several
      regimes, and three axes switch independently.
    </p>

    <dl class="axes">
      {axes.map((a) => (
        <div class="axis">
          <dt>{a.name} <span class="axis-on">on {a.on}</span></dt>
          <dd>{a.body}</dd>
        </div>
      ))}
    </dl>

    <p class="cap-body">
      Because the classification is read off the field, a regime change is an
      event the run finds rather than a station it is told to switch at. Every
      transition lands in the provenance log:
    </p>

    <pre><code>{regimeLog}</code></pre>

    <p class="cap-body">
      One descent moves through orbit-like dynamics, slip flow, continuum flow,
      comms blackout, and reacquisition in one uninterrupted program.
    </p>

    <p class="cap-more">
      <a href="/tutorial/stage-1-corridor/">Walk 1: the classifier in the stack</a>
      <a href="/blueprints/handle-regime-change/">Blueprint: handle a regime change</a>
    </p>
  </article>

  <!-- 3 -->
  <article class="cap panel corner-brackets rise" style="--i:2">
    <div class="cap-head">
      <p class="cap-ix num">03</p>
      <div>
        <h3>Native multiphysics</h3>
        <p class="cap-claim">Several disciplines step one shared field.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="cap-body">
      A coupling stack is a static cons-tuple of physics stages stepping one
      shared field:
    </p>

    <pre><code>{coupling}</code></pre>

    <p class="cap-body">
      Vibrational relaxation, reacting plasma chemistry, regime classification,
      steered aerodynamic force, a 17-state error-state Kalman navigation
      engine, and a bounded-correction safety gate, in one loop body. Stages
      communicate through named fields on the evolved state, and an
      <code>Err</code> from any stage short-circuits the whole step.
    </p>

    <p class="cap-body">
      The evolved electron density gates which measurements the Kalman filter
      may fold. The Knudsen number selects the governing model. The safety
      gate’s clamped bank command is flown by the aero stage and steers the
      trajectory that sets the next step’s freestream. Fluid dynamics,
      estimation, and control close one loop.
    </p>

    <ul class="cap-nums">
      <li>Plasma retropulsion descent, blackout exit to touchdown: sixteen gates in 333.6 s.</li>
      <li>Precision is a type parameter: f32, f64, or 106-bit, switched at one alias.</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="cap-more">
      <a href="/tutorial/">The three-walk tutorial</a>
      <a href="/blueprints/couple-multiphysics/">Blueprint: couple multiphysics</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</section>

<style>
